WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.050 --> 00:00:02.383
CLIFF REDEKER: Welcome to
another Talks at Google event.

00:00:02.383 --> 00:00:03.040
I am Cliff.

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:06.100
The man of the hour we have
here is Brian Kelly, the CEO

00:00:06.100 --> 00:00:07.613
and Founder of thepointsguy.com.

00:00:07.613 --> 00:00:08.790
Welcome to Google.

00:00:08.790 --> 00:00:09.300
BRIAN KELLY: Thanks
for having me.

00:00:09.300 --> 00:00:09.653
CLIFF REDEKER: Thank you.

00:00:09.653 --> 00:00:10.814
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:10.814 --> 00:00:12.690
All right.

00:00:12.690 --> 00:00:15.954
So we have a lot of travel
fans in the audience.

00:00:15.954 --> 00:00:17.870
We're also streaming it
live to Google offices

00:00:17.870 --> 00:00:19.820
worldwide and the folks
at home at YouTube.

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:22.040
And so had a few questions
to go through right now,

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:24.670
and then we'll have time for
some open audience Q&amp;A as well.

00:00:24.670 --> 00:00:27.657
So if there's any burning
questions about your points

00:00:27.657 --> 00:00:30.240
or if you have a wallet full of
credit cards you need audited,

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:31.661
just let us know.

00:00:31.661 --> 00:00:32.619
We'll make that happen.

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:34.540
BRIAN KELLY: I actually tried
to do a wallet audit at lunch

00:00:34.540 --> 00:00:34.860
today.

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:36.680
So if you want to show
me your assortment,

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:38.816
I can whip you into shape.

00:00:38.816 --> 00:00:40.440
CLIFF REDEKER: We
can make that happen.

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:43.424
And, of course, Googlers are
really passionate about travel.

00:00:43.424 --> 00:00:45.340
We have that small thing
called Google Flights

00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:47.750
search, the ITA Matrix,
the hotel bookings.

00:00:47.750 --> 00:00:49.919
So we're really
passionate about that.

00:00:49.919 --> 00:00:52.210
And that, in fact, leads me
to my first question, which

00:00:52.210 --> 00:00:53.780
is really about technology.

00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:56.430
And so it seems that
a lot of this game,

00:00:56.430 --> 00:00:59.170
a lot of the frequent
flyer mile program

00:00:59.170 --> 00:01:01.810
is built on this almost
Cold War race of,

00:01:01.810 --> 00:01:04.450
who has the most information,
and whose computer system

00:01:04.450 --> 00:01:07.410
is 30 years old to load mistake
fares, and stuff like that?

00:01:07.410 --> 00:01:09.860
Like, how do you view
the role of technology

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:11.610
in the travel industry,
and also in miles?

00:01:11.610 --> 00:01:14.151
BRIAN KELLY: Well, I think in
general in the travel industry,

00:01:14.151 --> 00:01:15.535
we're still way behind.

00:01:15.535 --> 00:01:17.660
I think one of the top
questions I always get asked

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:19.035
is, I have these
amount of miles.

00:01:19.035 --> 00:01:19.800
Where can I go?

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:21.970
And there still really
is no perfect system

00:01:21.970 --> 00:01:27.040
that will actually correspond
with airline award inventory.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:30.185
You know, the airlines are
very protective of that data

00:01:30.185 --> 00:01:33.150
with sites like AwardWallet
for tracking your miles.

00:01:33.150 --> 00:01:35.010
Some airlines even
cut off access.

00:01:35.010 --> 00:01:37.960
So we're actually pretty far
behind, I think, in general.

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:39.960
But that's where
opportunity lies.

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:42.010
As you mentioned, mistake fares.

00:01:42.010 --> 00:01:43.600
Deals spread like wildfire.

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:49.012
And we have seen in 2016 more
crazy deals. $200 to Auckland.

00:01:49.012 --> 00:01:53.470
And you know, last year we
had the $185 to Abu Dhabi.

00:01:53.470 --> 00:01:56.677
So it's still a good time
to be in this sphere.

00:01:56.677 --> 00:01:57.510
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah.

00:01:57.510 --> 00:02:00.280
Do you see a push on the
credit card companies,

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:02.880
the airlines to try
to catch up on it?

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:03.712
Or is it just--

00:02:03.712 --> 00:02:05.920
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah, I mean,
it's a cat-and-mouse game.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:07.420
You know, Chase
recently instituted,

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:09.990
if you've had five cards
within the last two years,

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:11.570
you can get some
of their products.

00:02:11.570 --> 00:02:13.857
And they're expanding
that, we've seen recently.

00:02:13.857 --> 00:02:15.440
You know, the game
definitely changes,

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:17.789
but it's by far from over.

00:02:17.789 --> 00:02:19.580
You have to maybe work
a little bit harder.

00:02:19.580 --> 00:02:21.520
But for those who
put time and effort

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:24.320
into learning the
ways of how to search

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:26.820
for availability that others
can't see, there's opportunity.

00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:28.028
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah, exactly.

00:02:28.028 --> 00:02:29.400
It's almost an arbitrage.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.440
And for a lot of folks just
starting out and keeping

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:34.690
track of their miles
and their points,

00:02:34.690 --> 00:02:36.280
they don't really
necessarily want

00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:38.820
to spend too much effort doing
it, don't want to go nuts.

00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:41.261
What can you tell them
about how to get started?

00:02:41.261 --> 00:02:42.760
And what are they
missing out by not

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:43.860
putting their
frequent flyer number

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:45.150
in on those
twice-a-year bookings?

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:47.180
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah, I mean, it's
not even-- a lot of people say,

00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:49.320
oh, I don't travel that much, so
I'm not going to get into this.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:50.611
But it's not even about travel.

00:02:50.611 --> 00:02:53.230
More miles will be minted
this year from non-travel.

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:55.230
So credit cards and
partner activity

00:02:55.230 --> 00:02:56.480
than from actually flying.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:00.292
And especially as airlines now
go into revenue-- next week

00:03:00.292 --> 00:03:01.750
whenever you fly
American Airlines,

00:03:01.750 --> 00:03:03.610
you'll receive miles
based on how much you

00:03:03.610 --> 00:03:07.166
paid, not how far you fly,
if you bank to American.

00:03:07.166 --> 00:03:09.040
You know, there are
still more ways than ever

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:10.050
to get miles and points.

00:03:10.050 --> 00:03:12.470
It's really about getting
the right credit card.

00:03:12.470 --> 00:03:14.220
It's really frequent
spender programs now.

00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:15.428
So get the right credit card.

00:03:15.428 --> 00:03:17.320
The bonuses are as high as ever.

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:21.320
So even though airlines are
raising the price of awards,

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:24.350
you know, sometimes
overnight, you

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:26.380
can get miles and
points all around you

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:27.590
for doing everyday things.

00:03:27.590 --> 00:03:27.810
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah.

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:30.390
And as these programs get more
homogenized, like you said,

00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:33.530
it's almost like a punch card
per dollar and everything.

00:03:33.530 --> 00:03:35.490
Is that a sign of the end times?

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:37.240
Like, is there still
a unique opportunity?

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:39.698
BRIAN KELLY: There's definitely
still unique opportunities.

00:03:39.698 --> 00:03:42.152
I just got back from-- I went
for three nights to Sydney

00:03:42.152 --> 00:03:43.360
and New Zealand this weekend.

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:45.460
I flew Alaska
Airlines 70,000 miles

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:47.651
and $42 Qantas first class.

00:03:47.651 --> 00:03:48.650
And I was sitting there.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:51.220
I'm like, $42 out of
pocket as I'm laying.

00:03:51.220 --> 00:03:53.340
And I'm just looking at
everyone going to coach.

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:56.780
And I'm like, those people
probably paid 20 times as much

00:03:56.780 --> 00:03:59.590
as I did, cash out of pocket.

00:03:59.590 --> 00:04:02.070
So the game is still there now.

00:04:02.070 --> 00:04:04.560
So the airlines have moved
to revenue based on earning.

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:08.080
Now if the airlines ever moved
to revenue-based redemptions

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:09.930
like Southwest and JetBlue.

00:04:09.930 --> 00:04:12.740
You know, American Airlines,
that will take the glory out

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:13.819
of the game, so to speak.

00:04:13.819 --> 00:04:15.860
I'm sure there'll be other
ways to get around it.

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:17.529
But right now, I
mean, these airlines

00:04:17.529 --> 00:04:19.820
still have these wonky charts.

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:22.190
Half the time, the airline,
because of bad technology

00:04:22.190 --> 00:04:25.150
and because they're working
on outdated systems,

00:04:25.150 --> 00:04:28.200
there's still so many
ways to maximize.

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:30.540
The fact that you can
fly San Diego to Istanbul

00:04:30.540 --> 00:04:32.860
is the same exact amount
of miles as, you know,

00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:35.770
Boston to Dublin makes no sense.

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:37.580
But I don't think
that those changes are

00:04:37.580 --> 00:04:38.788
going to happen anytime soon.

00:04:38.788 --> 00:04:40.320
So even if you're
new to the game,

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:43.369
there's still plenty
to take advantage of,

00:04:43.369 --> 00:04:44.160
as you do yourself.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:44.570
CLIFF REDEKER: Well, thank you.

00:04:44.570 --> 00:04:45.522
Thank you.

00:04:45.522 --> 00:04:46.480
I try every little bit.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:48.530
I'm not quite up
to TPG territory.

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:50.580
But one mile at a
time, as you said.

00:04:50.580 --> 00:04:51.890
[LAUGH]

00:04:51.890 --> 00:04:55.800
So I also was curious as well,
like, the other news this year

00:04:55.800 --> 00:05:00.210
is the sizable decline in price
for fares for premium cabins.

00:05:00.210 --> 00:05:02.240
And so it's gotten to
the point, you know,

00:05:02.240 --> 00:05:04.310
there's amazing things
on British Airways

00:05:04.310 --> 00:05:05.280
and flights to Europe.

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:07.940
As you were saying,
flights to New Zealand.

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:10.800
Are we landing on sort
of an equilibrium price?

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:13.030
Like, the price is
right on these fares.

00:05:13.030 --> 00:05:15.110
Like, is that a bad
thing when more people

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:17.250
are paying versus redemption?

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:18.684
Or how do you see that balance?

00:05:18.684 --> 00:05:19.350
BRIAN KELLY: No.

00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:21.080
I mean-- well, I think
the first thing is

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:22.509
free upgrades are disappearing.

00:05:22.509 --> 00:05:23.800
And that's indisputable, right?

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:25.670
So if you're just
getting into the game now

00:05:25.670 --> 00:05:27.600
and you want to race
to get elite status,

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:30.730
and you're going to expect to
get free upgrades all the time,

00:05:30.730 --> 00:05:33.480
likely set your expectations--
now with elite status,

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:36.850
especially at the very highest
tiers, is still very valuable.

00:05:36.850 --> 00:05:38.440
So I think it's
actually a good place.

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:41.080
In the past, airlines priced
first class and business class

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:43.230
so ridiculously
and out of touch.

00:05:43.230 --> 00:05:46.550
10 times the price of economy
for, like, a little bit

00:05:46.550 --> 00:05:48.024
of a recliner and crappy food.

00:05:48.024 --> 00:05:49.440
So now the airlines
are actually--

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:53.880
I think pricing is becoming
more sane and affordable.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:55.632
And that's great for consumers.

00:05:55.632 --> 00:05:57.340
But that's also why
I think people should

00:05:57.340 --> 00:05:58.480
diversify miles and points.

00:05:58.480 --> 00:05:59.590
It's not just about airfare.

00:05:59.590 --> 00:06:01.298
So many people are
myopically focused on,

00:06:01.298 --> 00:06:03.900
let me just get airline miles
for the free-- but hotels

00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:07.217
and other experiences,
you should really

00:06:07.217 --> 00:06:08.550
diversify your miles and points.

00:06:08.550 --> 00:06:09.980
And that's, I think,
one key thing I

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:10.920
would like everyone to get away.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:13.090
If you're just getting
into this, don't just,

00:06:13.090 --> 00:06:14.190
oh, I fly United Airlines.

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:16.481
I'm going to get United credit
card and United, United,

00:06:16.481 --> 00:06:17.370
United.

00:06:17.370 --> 00:06:18.340
Try to diversify.

00:06:18.340 --> 00:06:21.484
Get transferable
points programs so

00:06:21.484 --> 00:06:22.900
that when it comes
time to redeem,

00:06:22.900 --> 00:06:23.770
you've got lots of options.

00:06:23.770 --> 00:06:24.590
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah, that's
what I was going to say.

00:06:24.590 --> 00:06:27.256
Like, with the big four
transferable points,

00:06:27.256 --> 00:06:29.380
it seems that the airlines
still have a lot of ways

00:06:29.380 --> 00:06:30.463
to go to catch up to that.

00:06:30.463 --> 00:06:31.800
Do you see that continuing?

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:35.030
Just keep banking to the
cities, the Chase, the Amex?

00:06:35.030 --> 00:06:35.780
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah.

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:37.810
I mean, so the relationships,
just so people don't-- these

00:06:37.810 --> 00:06:39.640
are huge profit
centers for airlines.

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:43.660
Frequent flyer programs are
arguably the most effective

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:45.190
marketing technique
ever created.

00:06:45.190 --> 00:06:48.300
So American Airlines just signed
on with Citi and Barclaycard

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:49.880
to issue their cards.

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:51.285
So that means more products.

00:06:51.285 --> 00:06:52.660
You know, so Citi
and Barclaycard

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:55.994
will be competing against each
other for American Airlines

00:06:55.994 --> 00:06:57.660
credit card business,
which is something

00:06:57.660 --> 00:06:58.510
we've never seen before.

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:00.330
Everyone thought they'd
just go with one partner.

00:07:00.330 --> 00:07:02.810
So there's tons and tons of
competition on the marketplace.

00:07:02.810 --> 00:07:06.080
You know, American Express
lost JetBlue to Barclaycard.

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:07.420
They lost Costco to Citi.

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:09.990
So this actually bodes
well for consumers.

00:07:09.990 --> 00:07:11.680
So once again, I
think my key point is,

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:13.460
even though these
are travel programs,

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:15.084
really, it's all
about the credit card.

00:07:15.084 --> 00:07:17.450
So getting the
right credit cards,

00:07:17.450 --> 00:07:19.580
getting it on huge bonuses,
and then beyond that,

00:07:19.580 --> 00:07:23.251
maximizing every single dollar
you spend is the way to win.

00:07:23.251 --> 00:07:25.500
CLIFF REDEKER: There's even
an app for that on the TPG

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:26.880
that will help you.

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:28.160
BRIAN KELLY: There is, TPG
To Go on the app store.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:29.010
CLIFF REDEKER: Yes.

00:07:29.010 --> 00:07:31.267
Android and iOS.

00:07:31.267 --> 00:07:32.350
BRIAN KELLY: Thanks a lot.

00:07:32.350 --> 00:07:33.183
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah.

00:07:33.183 --> 00:07:34.280
I do what I can.

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:37.070
So then also, moving
the conversation again

00:07:37.070 --> 00:07:38.380
towards the infrequent flyers.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:40.630
Like, are there
three basic things

00:07:40.630 --> 00:07:42.755
that you'd recommend people
do just starting out?

00:07:42.755 --> 00:07:44.640
And of course, there's
articles on TV,

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:46.120
thepointsguy.com to that end.

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:49.304
But anything that people
miss from the get-go?

00:07:49.304 --> 00:07:49.970
BRIAN KELLY: No.

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:52.344
I mean, I think just sign up
for frequent flyer programs.

00:07:52.344 --> 00:07:54.440
But instead, if you're
flying American Airlines,

00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:55.730
you don't have to bank
your frequent flyer

00:07:55.730 --> 00:07:56.830
miles to American Airlines.

00:07:56.830 --> 00:07:58.820
So if you buy a really
cheap ticket on American,

00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:01.486
you may want to actually bank to
British Airways, their partner,

00:08:01.486 --> 00:08:03.980
which actually can
provide amazing value.

00:08:03.980 --> 00:08:06.054
And once you're redeeming
miles, don't assume,

00:08:06.054 --> 00:08:07.470
if I've got British
Airways miles,

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:08.700
I'm going to redeem
on British Airways.

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:10.174
That's often the
worst redemption.

00:08:10.174 --> 00:08:11.840
So you have to think
counterintuitively.

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:12.790
It makes no sense.

00:08:12.790 --> 00:08:14.748
You think, well, why
would British Airways make

00:08:14.748 --> 00:08:16.057
better redemptions on partners?

00:08:16.057 --> 00:08:18.390
Just stop asking yourself
those questions, because logic

00:08:18.390 --> 00:08:20.360
never works with
airlines and hotels.

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:21.610
You just take advantage of it.

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:24.790
So think outside the box.

00:08:24.790 --> 00:08:26.707
You know, like, we have
over 9,000 blog posts.

00:08:26.707 --> 00:08:29.290
We're actually going through a
major web redesign as we speak.

00:08:29.290 --> 00:08:31.236
And hopefully this
fall, we're relaunching,

00:08:31.236 --> 00:08:32.610
and it's going to
be much easier.

00:08:32.610 --> 00:08:33.526
Right now, it's funny.

00:08:33.526 --> 00:08:35.485
People I'm like, just go
Google the points guy,

00:08:35.485 --> 00:08:37.276
and then put your topic
in, and then you'll

00:08:37.276 --> 00:08:38.220
see all the results.

00:08:38.220 --> 00:08:41.470
So thank you to the search team
for making it so easy to search

00:08:41.470 --> 00:08:44.020
our hot mess of a website.

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:45.600
I think that was two things.

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:47.490
The third is just think
counterintuitively.

00:08:47.490 --> 00:08:48.080
You all are very--

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:48.630
[MICROPHONE SQUEAK]

00:08:48.630 --> 00:08:49.270
--smart.

00:08:49.270 --> 00:08:49.770
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah.

00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:50.478
BRIAN KELLY: God?

00:08:50.478 --> 00:08:51.176
[LAUGH]

00:08:51.749 --> 00:08:52.790
Think counterintuitively.

00:08:52.790 --> 00:08:54.532
This is a fun game
that can be won.

00:08:54.532 --> 00:08:55.990
Yes, it takes a
little bit of time.

00:08:55.990 --> 00:08:57.490
But when you think
about this hobby,

00:08:57.490 --> 00:09:00.870
I think it's amazing that
this hobby can actually help

00:09:00.870 --> 00:09:02.367
you travel more and spend less.

00:09:02.367 --> 00:09:04.950
