trip can be banked

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:33.210
at a certain rate
towards another trip.

00:12:33.210 --> 00:12:36.950
There's companies like Upside
and Rocketrip and TravelPerk.

00:12:36.950 --> 00:12:38.230
What do you make of those?

00:12:38.230 --> 00:12:40.670
Like, how does that
change the optimization?

00:12:40.670 --> 00:12:41.450
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah.

00:12:41.450 --> 00:12:42.440
And Upside's really interesting.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:43.356
We just met with them.

00:12:43.356 --> 00:12:44.780
So they basically
give gift cards

00:12:44.780 --> 00:12:46.777
to business travelers
for being flexible,

00:12:46.777 --> 00:12:47.860
which I think makes sense.

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:50.050
I mean, to be honest,
when I was on Wall Street,

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:51.466
there were times
when I would book

00:12:51.466 --> 00:12:53.980
last minute to get the full
fare to automatic upgrade.

00:12:53.980 --> 00:12:59.755
So when business
travelers are incentivized

00:12:59.755 --> 00:13:01.590
to travel better if
you book last minute,

00:13:01.590 --> 00:13:04.440
I mean, I think it makes
sense if the company can

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:07.760
en masse save money by
leaving a day early or so.

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:09.880
But I mean,
Rocketmiles, all those.

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:13.670
They're nice little
boosts of bonuses

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:14.740
whenever you book hotels.

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:17.720
But you know, Upside
is interesting.

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:21.160
I won't really comment on it
until I can fully test it,

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:22.490
but the concept is interesting.

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:22.640
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah.

