So we take a look at all three
of the major Hyatt's points,

00:27:15.670 --> 00:27:16.460
locations.

00:27:16.460 --> 00:27:19.270
So we're trying to help
consumers make better decisions

00:27:19.270 --> 00:27:20.834
with their points via video.

00:27:20.834 --> 00:27:23.250
CLIFF REDEKER: Is there anything
that people may not fully

00:27:23.250 --> 00:27:24.750
appreciate about TPG TV?

00:27:24.750 --> 00:27:27.130
Is it a different experience
when you go into the Hyatts

00:27:27.130 --> 00:27:27.976
with a camera crew?

00:27:27.976 --> 00:27:29.350
And how do you
keep objectivity--

00:27:29.350 --> 00:27:31.350
BRIAN KELLY: You know we do
have get permissions to fly.

00:27:31.350 --> 00:27:32.410
And I actually didn't
think the airlines were

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:33.660
going to let us film on board.

00:27:33.660 --> 00:27:36.410
But almost every single
airline has allowed us to film

00:27:36.410 --> 00:27:37.407
on board.

00:27:37.407 --> 00:27:38.990
I mean, I think at
the end of the day,

00:27:38.990 --> 00:27:40.990
the product is what
you want to see.

00:27:40.990 --> 00:27:41.876
And I'm six foot 7".

00:27:41.876 --> 00:27:44.000
So whenever I fly in a
product, if I'm comfortable,

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:45.840
like, chances are you
probably will be too.

00:27:48.752 --> 00:27:51.210
And really, it's not about the
flight review as much as how

00:27:51.210 --> 00:27:54.420
you can actually fly to Africa
for $5.60 using Delta miles.

00:27:54.420 --> 00:27:56.980
That's one of the best
ways-- Delta miles are really

00:27:56.980 --> 00:27:58.660
devalued, but to
Africa, it's amazing.

00:27:58.660 --> 00:28:02.350
So they fly JFK to Accra.

00:28:02.350 --> 00:28:03.350
And Africa's amazing.

00:28:03.350 --> 00:28:05.183
Probably one of my
favorite places to visit.

00:28:05.183 --> 00:28:07.440
So the point of TPG TV
on flying Delta to Accra

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:08.800
is showing the product.

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:11.905
It's a pretty decent
business class product.

00:28:11.905 --> 00:28:12.580
So, yeah.

00:28:12.580 --> 00:28:15.400
I mean, tweaking video's
an interesting beast.

00:28:15.400 --> 00:28:17.999
And obviously, we
hear in social media,

00:28:17.999 --> 00:28:19.040
it's video, video, video.

00:28:19.040 --> 00:28:20.590
We see all of our
major news networks

00:28:20.590 --> 00:28:22.526
now switching to video
and Facebook Live.

00:28:22.526 --> 00:28:24.400
So I think we're adapting
and we're learning.

00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:27.740
But I think we've gotten great
feedback on the episodes.

00:28:27.740 --> 00:28:30.275
And it's meant to
entertain and educate.

00:28:30.275 --> 00:28:31.650
CLIFF REDEKER:
And like you said,

00:28:31.650 --> 00:28:33.066
there's a big
education component.

00:28:33.066 --> 00:28:36.211
So it's not like, what's
best dim sum in Hong Kong,

00:28:36.211 --> 00:28:36.710
necessarily.

00:28:36.710 --> 00:28:38.980
Like, there's other ways
to get that information.

00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:39.280
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah.

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:41.738
So we do have some of those
fun-- like the robot restaurant

00:28:41.738 --> 00:28:43.354
and eating blowfish in Osaka.

00:28:43.354 --> 00:28:44.520
CLIFF REDEKER: You survived.

00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:46.010
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah, I survived.

00:28:46.010 --> 00:28:48.382
Fugu blowfish is
actually amazing.

00:28:48.382 --> 00:28:50.090
I highly recommend
it, but only at, like,

00:28:50.090 --> 00:28:51.110
the right restaurants.

00:28:51.110 --> 00:28:52.890
So stay tuned for
the TPG TV episode

00:28:52.890 --> 00:28:54.980
where we tell you the right
one to go to in Osaka.

00:28:54.980 --> 00:28:55.350
CLIFF REDEKER: Nice.

00:28:55.350 --> 00:28:55.850
Nice.

00:28:55.850 --> 00:28:56.599
Very cool.

00:28:56.599 --> 00:28:58.390
So I have some questions
about travel life,

00:28:58.390 --> 00:29:00.370
but if you all in the audience
have some questions as well,

00:29:00.370 --> 00:29:02.036
we'll have a mic that
circulates around.

00:29:02.036 --> 00:29:03.780
So raise your hand.

00:29:03.780 --> 00:29:07.830
We'll seek you out
and toss it your way.

00:29:07.830 --> 00:29:13.350
So you know, travel life,
how do you value the effort

00:29:13.350 --> 00:29:14.680
behind getting these points?

00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:16.179
Like, are there
diminishing returns?

00:29:16.179 --> 00:29:19.200
Like, how do you calculate
these monthly valuations

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:20.310
that you post on TV?

00:29:20.310 --> 00:29:22.600
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah, so we do
a monthly valuation where

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:24.764
we-- basically, it's a ranking.

00:29:24.764 --> 00:29:26.430
Not all points are
created equal, right?

00:29:26.430 --> 00:29:28.555
Some point currencies are
much, much more valuable.

00:29:28.555 --> 00:29:30.450
Like, Starwood points
are the most valuable.

00:29:30.450 --> 00:29:33.230
And then on the flip side,
like, Spirit Airlines rewards,

00:29:33.230 --> 00:29:38.156
like, expire after a week
if you don't punch yourself

00:29:38.156 --> 00:29:38.655
in the face.

00:29:38.655 --> 00:29:40.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:41.440 --> 00:29:43.801
We're going to make them
much more scientific.

00:29:43.801 --> 00:29:45.300
But the thing is
with these, there's

00:29:45.300 --> 00:29:47.716
billions of permutations of
how you can use points, right?

00:29:47.716 --> 00:29:49.840
Some people would rather
go twice in economy.

00:29:49.840 --> 00:29:52.440
You know, and I've just flown
the Latun-- or the Qantas

00:29:52.440 --> 00:29:52.940
first class.

00:29:52.940 --> 00:29:54.398
It was a $9,000
ticket, and I spent

00:29:54.398 --> 00:29:55.950
$42, which sounds amazing.

00:29:55.950 --> 00:29:58.020
But you know, I wasn't
going to spend 18 grand

00:29:58.020 --> 00:29:59.820
to fly because I have
millions of miles,

00:29:59.820 --> 00:30:01.080
so what's the real value?

00:30:01.080 --> 00:30:02.931
There is no right answer.

00:30:02.931 --> 00:30:04.680
But the fact of the
matter is that a bunch

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:06.055
of other people
on that plane did

00:30:06.055 --> 00:30:09.450
spend $9,000, or at least full
fare business and upgraded.

00:30:09.450 --> 00:30:12.980
So the value of
miles is amazing.

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:16.980
But we're going to be
trying to put a little bit

00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:20.320
more technology into
the ease of redeeming.

00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:21.820
But at the end of
the day, you know,

00:30:21.820 --> 00:30:23.361
there's always
surveys that come out.

00:30:23.361 --> 00:30:25.280
The best frequent flyer
miles in the world

00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:27.215
are-- and it's like
Southwest, because you

00:30:27.215 --> 00:30:28.340
can use it on every flight.

00:30:28.340 --> 00:30:28.964
I'm like, yeah.

00:30:28.964 --> 00:30:32.474
But Southwest is pointless if
you want to go to Australia,

00:30:32.474 --> 00:30:34.140
or don't want to fly
coach domestically.

00:30:34.140 --> 00:30:38.230
So there's no one right program.

00:30:38.230 --> 00:30:41.212
And for me, I mean, it's all
on the credit card spend.

00:30:41.212 --> 00:30:42.670
That's how I make
most of my miles.

00:30:42.670 --> 00:30:44.020
I also do buy a lot of miles.

00:30:44.020 --> 00:30:48.800
So Alaska Airlines sells points
or miles for about $0.02 a pop.

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:51.830
So my 70,000 miles I used
for the one-way Qantas first

00:30:51.830 --> 00:30:53.950
cost me about $1,400.

00:30:53.950 --> 00:30:56.140
So you can buy miles,
and airlines still

00:30:56.140 --> 00:31:00.340
drastically discount miles to
usually around $0.02 a pop.

00:31:00.340 --> 00:31:04.169
So if you value miles
or need to top up,

00:31:04.169 --> 00:31:05.960
buying miles can still
make a lot of sense.

00:31:05.960 --> 00:31:08.279
But just be warned,
when you buy miles,

00:31:08.279 --> 00:31:09.570
they could devalue at any time.

00:31:09.570 --> 00:31:12.480
So have a plan of
attack when using them,

00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:13.580
and know how to use them.

00:31:13.580 --> 00:31:15.690
CLIFF REDEKER: And even the
posting, the delay for posting

00:31:15.690 --> 00:31:17.660
can be something that
you need to worry about.

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:18.410
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah.

00:31:18.410 --> 00:31:20.856
CLIFF REDEKER: With the
transferable credit cards.

00:31:20.856 --> 00:31:22.730
And of course, you know,
your work is travel.

00:31:22.730 --> 00:31:23.800
Travel is your work.

00:31:23.800 --> 00:31:27.010
How do you balance your
sort of personal life

00:31:27.010 --> 00:31:28.601
with the jet-setting adventures?

00:31:28.601 --> 00:31:29.350
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah.

00:31:29.350 --> 00:31:30.390
That's hard.

00:31:30.390 --> 00:31:31.403
I'm still learning.

00:31:31.403 --> 00:31:32.134
[LAUGH]

00:31:32.134 --> 00:31:34.550
Because I actually was sitting
on the plane the other day.

00:31:34.550 --> 00:31:35.924
I'm like, I'm
addicted to travel.

00:31:35.924 --> 00:31:38.090
Like, I flew to
Auckland for three days,

00:31:38.090 --> 00:31:39.930
and then flew in on Tuesday.

00:31:39.930 --> 00:31:41.490
And we had a
300-person event in LA.

00:31:41.490 --> 00:31:44.420
And people were like,
who's this monster?

00:31:44.420 --> 00:31:45.880
Like, how do you
just keep going?

00:31:45.880 --> 00:31:48.052
But it's what I love, too.

00:31:48.052 --> 00:31:48.760
And it's amazing.

00:31:48.760 --> 00:31:50.470
With points, flying
first and business class

00:31:50.470 --> 00:31:52.678
to Australia for three days
isn't that big of a deal.

00:31:52.678 --> 00:31:54.520
I actually wasn't hung--
or, not hung over.

00:31:54.520 --> 00:31:57.300
I wasn't jet lagged at all.

00:31:57.300 --> 00:31:57.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:57.800 --> 00:31:58.450
CLIFF REDEKER:
That Qantas lounge

00:31:58.450 --> 00:32:00.400
in LAX, though, they've
got the ice wine.

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:01.230
I'm just saying.

00:32:01.230 --> 00:32:01.950
BRIAN KELLY: I actually
didn't drink at all.

00:32:01.950 --> 00:32:04.602
I'm writing my first book
on points and my stories.

00:32:04.602 --> 00:32:06.060
So the whole point
of this trip was

00:32:06.060 --> 00:32:08.950
to sequester myself with
no Wi-Fi, which Qantas

00:32:08.950 --> 00:32:10.080
doesn't have, thankfully.

00:32:10.080 --> 00:32:12.330
And I actually got a ton of
writing done on the plane.

00:32:12.330 --> 00:32:14.345
So that's actually what
I love about travel.

00:32:14.345 --> 00:32:16.840
On the ground, so I'm on
Snapchat, Twitter, Facebook,

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:17.440
Instagram.

00:32:17.440 --> 00:32:21.420
Constant employees
nagging me all the time.

00:32:21.420 --> 00:32:23.150
And I actually just
want to raise--

00:32:23.150 --> 00:32:23.450
CLIFF REDEKER: We've got some--

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:25.560
BRIAN KELLY: We've got my
editorial director James Cury.

00:32:25.560 --> 00:32:25.790
Here.

00:32:25.790 --> 00:32:26.860
He manages all of our content.

00:32:26.860 --> 00:32:28.200
He came from "Details" magazine.

00:32:28.200 --> 00:32:31.930
Scott Kidder, who's my CEO,
came from a site, Gawker Media.

00:32:31.930 --> 00:32:34.514
And Kate, who's my longest
standing employee--

00:32:34.514 --> 00:32:36.180
I don't even know
what she does anymore.

00:32:36.180 --> 00:32:38.620
She's basically the
wizard behind the machine

00:32:38.620 --> 00:32:40.610
that, like, makes
everything run on the site.

00:32:40.610 --> 00:32:42.359
She knows where all
the bodies are buried.

00:32:42.359 --> 00:32:44.914
So I can't not have her around.

00:32:44.914 --> 00:32:45.930
CLIFF REDEKER: Cool.

00:32:45.930 --> 00:32:47.471
BRIAN KELLY: She's
also the co-parent

00:32:47.471 --> 00:32:48.600
of my cute dog, Miles.

00:32:48.600 --> 00:32:50.310
CLIFF REDEKER: Who unfortunately
could not make it today.

00:32:50.310 --> 00:32:51.560
Google's a dog-friendly place.

00:32:51.560 --> 00:32:52.220
But next time.

00:32:52.220 --> 00:32:54.094
BRIAN KELLY: I didn't
want to be overshadowed

00:32:54.094 --> 00:32:57.232
by my adorably cute blue French
bulldog, is the real reason.

00:32:57.232 --> 00:32:58.440
CLIFF REDEKER: As it happens.

00:32:58.440 --> 00:33:00.680
What would you say your
philosophy of travel is?

00:33:00.680 --> 00:33:01.970
Like, when you go to
a new destination,

00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:02.770
how do you approach it?

00:33:02.770 --> 00:33:03.644
What do you look for?

00:33:03.644 --> 00:33:06.180
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah,
unlike some people

00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:07.880
who are addicted
in the travel, I

00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:10.305
travel because I do
love the destination.

00:33:10.305 --> 00:33:11.970
You know, being
on airplanes, even

00:33:11.970 --> 00:33:15.340
in the best first-class
cabin is still exhausting,

00:33:15.340 --> 00:33:17.060
tiring on your body.

00:33:17.060 --> 00:33:20.970
But the world, there's just so
much-- there's so many amazing

00:33:20.970 --> 00:33:26.330
places to see in the world
that it's worth it to me.

00:33:26.330 --> 00:33:27.750
So I travel for the destination.

00:33:27.750 --> 00:33:28.833
It brings family together.

00:33:28.833 --> 00:33:31.892
I just took my parents to Africa
using points, first class.

00:33:31.892 --> 00:33:34.350
So they didn't even feel guilty
that I spent a ton of money

00:33:34.350 --> 00:33:35.477
on them.

00:33:35.477 --> 00:33:37.810
But I'm closer with my parents
now because of that trip.

00:33:37.810 --> 00:33:40.018
The trip was life changing
in so many different ways.

00:33:40.018 --> 00:33:41.952
So travel changes your life.

00:33:41.952 --> 00:33:43.910
I wish more people would
travel and kind of get

00:33:43.910 --> 00:33:46.640
the world mindset.

00:33:46.640 --> 00:33:49.320
And it also helps realize, we
do have a lot of things amazing

00:33:49.320 --> 00:33:51.665
here, but there's a lot
of things we can change.

00:33:51.665 --> 00:33:53.800
The blanket statement,
America's the best.

00:33:53.800 --> 00:33:56.370
Like, it's not actually
true when you see the world.

00:33:56.370 --> 00:33:59.220
CLIFF REDEKER: And it's
moving beyond the room service

00:33:59.220 --> 00:34:01.620
and the hotel
restaurant to see what

00:34:01.620 --> 00:34:03.161
life is like on the grounds.

00:34:03.161 --> 00:34:03.660
Cool.

00:34:03.660 --> 00:34:06.542
Are there audience
questions at this time?

00:34:06.542 --> 00:34:08.199
Any burning questions so far?

00:34:08.199 --> 00:34:11.020
If not, you can
hold them for later.

00:34:11.020 --> 00:34:15.360
I did have a question
from Angela, in fact.

00:34:15.360 --> 00:34:18.179
What travel experiences have
influenced your future travel

00:34:18.179 --> 00:34:20.870
destinations, and why?

00:34:20.870 --> 00:34:23.120
BRIAN KELLY: Well, actually,
I have a fear of heights,

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:25.263
which is kind of funny.

00:34:25.263 --> 00:34:27.179
Someone actually tweeted
me, isn't that ironic

00:34:27.179 --> 00:34:30.086
that you're really tall
and afraid of heights?

00:34:30.086 --> 00:34:31.960
But I've been confronting
my fear of heights.

00:34:31.960 --> 00:34:34.780
I did hot air ballooning
in Turkey in Cappadocia.

00:34:34.780 --> 00:34:37.929
I highly recommend--
maybe wait a little while

00:34:37.929 --> 00:34:38.900
as things settle down.

00:34:38.900 --> 00:34:40.941
But actually, Turkey's
still a great destination.

00:34:40.941 --> 00:34:43.111
We had one of our
writers there last week.

00:34:43.111 --> 00:34:45.610
And I think it's kind of fun
to travel to conquer your fear.

00:34:45.610 --> 00:34:47.152
So in Auckland, I
jumped off of the--

00:34:47.152 --> 00:34:48.193
CLIFF REDEKER: Oh, right.

00:34:48.193 --> 00:34:49.040
The Sky Tower.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:51.399
BRIAN KELLY: The SkyJump,
which was terrifying.

00:34:51.399 --> 00:34:53.690
And being at the edge-- it
was pulling me off the edge.

00:34:53.690 --> 00:34:56.164
And the guy was like, put
both feet at the edge.

00:34:56.164 --> 00:34:57.580
And I'm like, it's
pulling me off.

00:34:57.580 --> 00:34:58.650
Am I unhooked yet?

00:34:58.650 --> 00:34:59.820
Like, I was panicking.

00:34:59.820 --> 00:35:02.832
But you know, the 10-second
almost free fall was amazing.

00:35:02.832 --> 00:35:05.290
So now I actually have skydiving
on the list, which I never

00:35:05.290 --> 00:35:06.242
thought I would do.

00:35:06.242 --> 00:35:08.200
So travel for me, I still
like to be pushed out

00:35:08.200 --> 00:35:09.650
of my comfort zone.

00:35:09.650 --> 00:35:11.570
My main place that
I love visiting

00:35:11.570 --> 00:35:13.250
is the continent of Africa.

00:35:13.250 --> 00:35:17.935
It is so unbelievably-- it's
inspiring, breathtaking.

00:35:17.935 --> 00:35:20.310
Safari's probably been-- I
just took my parents on safari

00:35:20.310 --> 00:35:22.330
in Tanzania.

00:35:22.330 --> 00:35:24.830
Sabi Sands and
Kruger's a great place.

00:35:24.830 --> 00:35:25.680
Go to South Africa.

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:27.638
If you guys are looking
for travel inspiration,

00:35:27.638 --> 00:35:30.500
South Africa is incredibly
affordable once you get there,

00:35:30.500 --> 00:35:31.490
and it's everything.

00:35:31.490 --> 00:35:33.190
You know, Cape Town's
a European city

00:35:33.190 --> 00:35:35.066
on the beach with penguins.

00:35:35.066 --> 00:35:36.690
You can drive to the
Cape of Good Hope.

00:35:36.690 --> 00:35:38.920
The wine country
outside of Cape Town

00:35:38.920 --> 00:35:43.410
is unbelievably,
insanely beautiful wines.

00:35:43.410 --> 00:35:44.550
And it's so affordable.

00:35:44.550 --> 00:35:47.321
The dollar is so
strong against Iran.

00:35:47.321 --> 00:35:49.320
And getting their on miles
is doable, especially

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:51.300
with the Middle
Eastern carriers.

00:35:51.300 --> 00:35:53.800
CLIFF REDEKER: And the
A380 to Johannesburg now.

00:35:53.800 --> 00:35:54.990
BRIAN KELLY: Yes.

00:35:54.990 --> 00:35:57.300
So, yeah.

00:35:57.300 --> 00:35:58.150
On Etihad right now.

00:35:58.150 --> 00:35:58.725
CLIFF REDEKER: Yeah.

00:35:58.725 --> 00:35:59.516
Or Emirates, right?

00:35:59.516 --> 00:36:00.829
BRIAN KELLY: On Emirates, yeah.

00:36:00.829 --> 00:36:02.620
CLIFF REDEKER: And do
you still scuba dive?

00:36:02.620 --> 00:36:04.410
I saw, like, the
progress of lessons,

00:36:04.410 --> 00:36:05.640
and haven't seen many posts.

00:36:05.640 --> 00:36:06.806
BRIAN KELLY: That was crazy.

00:36:06.806 --> 00:36:07.840
So I love scuba diving.

00:36:07.840 --> 00:36:11.240
So the world is more covered
in water than it is land.

00:36:11.240 --> 00:36:14.530
So underwater is
unbelievably beautiful.

00:36:14.530 --> 00:36:16.740
I got scuba certified
for a year and a half.

00:36:16.740 --> 00:36:19.220
It was Great Barrier
Reef, Maldives.

00:36:19.220 --> 00:36:21.400
My favorite dive actually
was in the Cayman Islands.

00:36:21.400 --> 00:36:22.340
It was like a video game.

00:36:22.340 --> 00:36:24.340
It was a cavern, and we
were just going through.

00:36:24.340 --> 00:36:27.040
And it was an absolute video
game of things I've never seen.

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:27.940
And I love sharks.

00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:29.065
They're my favorite animal.

00:36:29.065 --> 00:36:31.760
And you realize sharks,
like, don't give

00:36:31.760 --> 00:36:33.130
a crap at all about people.

00:36:33.130 --> 00:36:36.090
This whole fear about sharks
is really interesting.

00:36:36.090 --> 00:36:38.930
But unfortunately, in
Maui, I was diving,

00:36:38.930 --> 00:36:41.550
and the next day, I felt like
there was water in my ear,

00:36:41.550 --> 00:36:44.777
and ended up going
deaf for nine days.

00:36:44.777 --> 00:36:46.360
Completely deaf in
my right ear, which

00:36:46.360 --> 00:36:48.693
apparently is a freak thing
that happens to some people.

00:36:48.693 --> 00:36:52.279
Because I tweeted about it,
and a couple other people--

00:36:52.279 --> 00:36:54.070
they said I may never
have my hearing back.

00:36:54.070 --> 00:36:55.850
I went to three
different hospitals,

00:36:55.850 --> 00:36:58.630
and they had to put a
syringe into my ear drum,

00:36:58.630 --> 00:37:00.600
and pumped it full of steroids.

00:37:00.600 --> 00:37:02.330
Which actually worked
two days later.

00:37:02.330 --> 00:37:04.860
I was at dinner, and
I heard a crackle.

00:37:04.860 --> 00:37:06.982
And then it finally came
back, pretty much 100%.

00:37:06.982 --> 00:37:08.440
CLIFF REDEKER:
That's good to hear.

00:37:08.440 --> 00:37:10.064
BRIAN KELLY: Not to
be a Debbie downer.

00:37:10.064 --> 00:37:11.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:11.040 --> 00:37:13.440
But I will get back
in the water one day.

00:37:13.440 --> 00:37:14.820
But not quite yet.

00:37:14.820 --> 00:37:15.180
CLIFF REDEKER: That's OK.

00:37:15.180 --> 00:37:16.090
BRIAN KELLY: Are you a diver?

00:37:16.090 --> 00:37:18.220
CLIFF REDEKER: Actually, I just
