in the back there,

00:45:46.910 --> 00:45:48.980
and then we'll grab
one here on the right.

00:45:48.980 --> 00:45:51.025
AUDIENCE: This is actually
a question from Ryan

00:45:51.025 --> 00:45:53.050
in our LAX Google office.

00:45:53.050 --> 00:45:55.390
Save reward versus
standard fare award.

00:45:55.390 --> 00:45:58.020
What's the best time
to buy save rewards?

00:45:58.020 --> 00:45:59.450
Six months out, two weeks out?

00:45:59.450 --> 00:46:01.040
What's the breakdown for that?

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:02.700
BRIAN KELLY: So save
rewards are awards

00:46:02.700 --> 00:46:04.033
at the very lowest level, right?

00:46:04.033 --> 00:46:06.645
So the goal is to always
find save rewards.

00:46:06.645 --> 00:46:08.270
Why give them more
miles than possible?

00:46:08.270 --> 00:46:13.060
So the problem is that the
airlines are holding them

00:46:13.060 --> 00:46:14.720
back longer and
longer to departure,

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:17.550
because shockingly,
airlines are, in the US,

00:46:17.550 --> 00:46:20.845
publicly traded companies
that want to maximize profit.

00:46:20.845 --> 00:46:23.340
They want to offer save rewards
so they can advertise it.

00:46:23.340 --> 00:46:25.574
But for every single
person all the time,

00:46:25.574 --> 00:46:26.740
they want you to spend more.

00:46:26.740 --> 00:46:29.440
So this is going back to
the flexibility thing.

00:46:29.440 --> 00:46:33.149
If you're risk-averse, I would
say, book a standard award.

00:46:33.149 --> 00:46:34.690
You know, I actually
just booked one.

00:46:34.690 --> 00:46:35.782
I'm going to Europe.

00:46:35.782 --> 00:46:37.490
I want to fly on the
nonstop Rome flight.

00:46:37.490 --> 00:46:38.864
Rome to New York
on a certain day

00:46:38.864 --> 00:46:41.780
that I have to be home for
a big meeting the next day.

00:46:41.780 --> 00:46:44.040
I have an AA elite
status, so I booked

00:46:44.040 --> 00:46:46.830
135,000 miles AA one way.

00:46:46.830 --> 00:46:48.410
It's a $4,000 ticket to buy.

00:46:48.410 --> 00:46:51.840
I don't want to connect randomly
in Dusseldorf for 12 hours.

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:54.820
So I have that 135k
standard award waiting,

00:46:54.820 --> 00:46:56.940
but I can change it
unlimited times for free,

00:46:56.940 --> 00:46:57.690
because I'm elite.

00:46:57.690 --> 00:46:59.810
And even if you're
not elite, AA,

00:46:59.810 --> 00:47:01.730
if they do open up
a save reward, which

00:47:01.730 --> 00:47:05.270
you can set an expert flier
alert, you can pay $150

00:47:05.270 --> 00:47:13.240
and get 57,500-- you know,
80,000 miles back, or whatever.

00:47:13.240 --> 00:47:15.350
And the same goes, you
know, if you fly Southwest,

00:47:15.350 --> 00:47:17.890
keep monitoring to make sure
that the price doesn't drop.

00:47:17.890 --> 00:47:19.800
Because all you do is call,
and you get a free credit

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:20.990
in your account when it drops.

00:47:20.990 --> 00:47:23.156
There's actually, at our
app launch the other night,

00:47:23.156 --> 00:47:26.190
a new company called
Earny-- E-A-R-N-Y--

00:47:26.190 --> 00:47:29.099
which is an app that'll
consistently check,

00:47:29.099 --> 00:47:31.390
if you have purchase protection
and you purchase items,

00:47:31.390 --> 00:47:34.095
it'll keep checking for
price drop, for hotels.

00:47:34.095 --> 00:47:36.220
So it's a really fascinating--
I haven't checked it

00:47:36.220 --> 00:47:38.390
out myself yet.

00:47:38.390 --> 00:47:43.250
But you can save tons of money
and miles by staying on it.

00:47:43.250 --> 00:47:44.770
And the week of
departure, airlines

00:47:44.770 --> 00:47:46.990
release tons and tons
of saver-level awards.

00:47:46.990 --> 00:47:49.540
So even if you're
booked on an American

00:47:49.540 --> 00:47:52.570
Air-- a US carrier
and their partner

00:47:52.570 --> 00:47:56.980
opens up-- almost always, I'd
say, go with Asian carriers

00:47:56.980 --> 00:48:00.120
or even European carriers
beat the US carriers.

00:48:00.120 --> 00:48:01.640
Not in all cases.

